  "prompt": "What is the basis of reservation in India?",
  "response": "In India, the reservation system is primarily based on the principles of social justice and equality, aimed at addressing historical discrimination and providing opportunities to historically marginalized and disadvantaged sections of society. The key bases of reservation in India are:\n\n1. Caste-based Reservation:\n- Scheduled Castes (SC)\n- Scheduled Tribes (ST)\n- Other Backward Classes (OBC)\n\n2. Historical Discrimination:\n- Addressing centuries of social exclusion and oppression\n- Providing equal opportunities in education, employment, and political representation\n\n3. Constitutional Provision:\n- Article 15(4) and Article 16(4) of the Indian Constitution\n- Allows state to make special provisions for socially and educationally backward classes\n\n4. Representation:\n- Ensuring proportional representation in:\n- Government jobs\n- Educational institutions\n- Political bodies\n\n5. Socio-economic Criteria:\n- Economic backwardness\n- Social marginalization\n- Limited access to resources and opportunities\n\n6. Affirmative Action:\n- Promoting social mobility\n- Reducing inequality\n- Empowering marginalized communities\n\nThe reservation system aims to create a more inclusive and equitable society by providing positive discrimination and supporting historically disadvantaged groups.",
